ustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) the idea of raising the SALT ded=
uction=E2=80=94which, in a sentiment typical of his red state compadres, he=
=E2=80=99s panned as =E2=80=9Ca gigantic deduction for the rich living in h=
igh-tax states.=E2=80=9D

It=E2=80=99s
too soon to speculate about whether Democrats will support another Trump ta=
x cut, to the extent they=E2=80=99re relevant to this process at all, but n=
o Democrats voted for the 2017 version. They winced in particular at that l=
egislation=E2=80=99s slashing of corporate tax rates. They also chafe at Re=
publicans=E2=80=99 =E2=80=9Cdeficits for me and not for thee=E2=80=9D appro=
ach, whereby G.O.P. members are happy to blow a hole in the budget for thei=
r top economic priority (tax cuts), but threaten to shut down the governmen=
t over Democrats=E2=80=99 preferred mode of deficit enhancement (entitlemen=
ts).

It=E2=80=99s still worth noting that the cap affects the constituents of th=
e most powerful Democrats: soon-to-be-Senate Minority Leader Chuck Schumer,=
 D.S.C.C. chair contender Kirsten Gillibrand, House Minority Leader Hakeem =
Jeffries, and speaker emerita Nancy Pelosi. But if past is prologue, they=
=E2=80=99ll be locked out of negotiations.

The Margin Problem

So, are blue states S.O.L. on SALT? =E2=80=9CYes and no,=E2=80=9D a New Yor=
k Democratic delegation staffer told me. =E2=80=9CThe dynamics of 2025 will=
 be different from 2017 because of the slim margin in the House. The votes =
of New York, New Jersey, and California can make a difference.=E2=80=9D Wha=
t he means is that back in 2017, a dozen Republicans voted against ( https:=
//clerk.house.gov/Votes/2017699?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-=
+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F22%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+=
